# Deploy / Publish

## User Commands

| Command | Scope | What it does |
|---------|-------|-------------|
| `/deploy` | **This project only** | `Build-And-Publish.ps1` + `IIS-DeployApp.ps1 -SiteName GenericLogHandler` + GrabScreenShot |
| `/deployAll` | **All apps** | `Build-And-Publish-ALL.ps1` + `IIS-RedeployAll.ps1` + GrabScreenShot |
| `/commit` | **This project only** | git add + commit + push (only files in this repo) |
| `/commitAll` | **All repos** | git add + commit + push across all affected repos |

**CRITICAL: NEVER use `IIS-RedeployAll.ps1` unless the user explicitly says `/deployAll`.** Redeploying all apps tears down and rebuilds 7 IIS virtual applications and takes 5+ minutes. For single-app changes, always use `IIS-DeployApp.ps1 -SiteName <name>`.

## /deploy (Single App Deploy)

When the user requests `/deploy` or `/publish` (without "All"):

1. **Build and publish this project only:**
   ```powershell
   pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File ".\Build-And-Publish.ps1"
   ```
2. **Deploy this app only to IIS:**
   ```powershell
   pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File "C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\WebSites\IIS-DeployApp\IIS-DeployApp.ps1" -SiteName GenericLogHandler
   ```
3. **Post-deploy verification:**
   ```powershell
   pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File "C:\opt\src\GrabScreenShot\Invoke-GrabScreenShot.ps1"
   ```

## /deployAll (All Apps Deploy)

Only when the user explicitly requests `/deployAll`:

1. **Build and publish all apps:**
   ```powershell
   pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File "C:\opt\src\DedgeAuth\Build-And-Publish-ALL.ps1"
   ```
2. **Redeploy all IIS apps:**
   ```powershell
   pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File "C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\WebSites\IIS-DeployApp\IIS-RedeployAll.ps1"
   ```
3. **Post-deploy verification:**
   ```powershell
   pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File "C:\opt\src\GrabScreenShot\Invoke-GrabScreenShot.ps1"
   ```

**When /deployAll is appropriate:**
- Any edit to `DedgeAuth.Client` (middleware, endpoints, extensions, options)
- Any edit to `DedgeAuth.Api` wwwroot assets (CSS, JS, HTML)
- Any edit to `DedgeAuth.Services` (seeder, auth service, JWT)
- Changes that affect multiple apps simultaneously

**Do NOT auto-deploy for:**
- Documentation-only changes (`.md`, `.mdc` files)
- Test files or scripts that don't affect deployed apps
- Changes the user explicitly says not to deploy

If either step fails, diagnose and fix the issue before proceeding.

## Live Environment

| Component | Server | URL / Port |
|-----------|--------|------------|
| **DedgeAuth API (IIS)** | `dedge-server` | `http://dedge-server/DedgeAuth/` (port 80) |
| **PostgreSQL database** | `t-no1fkxtst-db` | Port **8432** |

- The API is **not** started locally -- it runs on `dedge-server` under IIS as a virtual application.
- The database runs on `t-no1fkxtst-db` on port **8432**.

When the user requests **/deploy** or **/publish**, perform the following in order:

## 1. Run Build-And-Publish.ps1

- From the project root, run: `.\Build-And-Publish.ps1`
- The script handles: version bump (Patch by default), publish to `C:\opt\src\DedgeSrc\DedgeSystemTools\Folders\DedgeCommon\Software\DedgeWinApps\DedgeAuth` (using WebApp-FileSystem profile), and deploying DedgePsh server scripts via `_deploy.ps1`.
- **Version:** Use the lowest level (Patch) unless the user explicitly asks for Major or Minor (e.g. `.\Build-And-Publish.ps1 -VersionPart Minor`).
- If the build or script fails, resolve errors before proceeding to git.

### Build-And-Publish-ALL.ps1

To rebuild DedgeAuth **and** all consumer apps that reference `DedgeAuth.Client`:

```powershell
.\Build-And-Publish-ALL.ps1           # Build DedgeAuth first, then all consumer apps
.\Build-And-Publish-ALL.ps1 -DryRun   # Show what would be built without building
.\Build-And-Publish-ALL.ps1 -SkipDedgeAuth  # Only rebuild consumer apps
```

- Scans `$env:OptPath\src` for `.csproj` files referencing `DedgeAuth.Client`
- Builds DedgeAuth first (auth server must be published before consumers)
- Then builds each discovered consumer app sequentially via its own `Build-And-Publish.ps1`

## Publishing Profile

- **ALWAYS use `WebApp-FileSystem.pubxml` -- it is the ONLY publish profile in the project**
- **Command:** `dotnet publish -c Release -p:PublishProfile=WebApp-FileSystem`
- **Publish (staging) location:** `C:\opt\src\DedgeSrc\DedgeSystemTools\Folders\DedgeCommon\Software\DedgeWinApps\DedgeAuth`
- **IIS install location:** `$env:OptPath\DedgeWinApps\DedgeAuth` (UNC: `C:\opt\src\DedgeSrc\DedgeSystemTools\Folders\Opt\DedgeWinApps\DedgeAuth`)
- The publish location is the staging area; `IIS-DeployApp.ps1` on the server copies from staging to the install location
- The profile uses FileSystem method and publishes as framework-dependent win-x64 runtime
- When using Build-And-Publish.ps1, it defaults to WebApp-FileSystem profile
- IIS on the server points at the install location, not the publish location
- **Do NOT create or suggest Web Deploy (MSDeploy) profiles -- they are not used in this project**
- **Do NOT run scripts remotely via WinRM/Invoke-Command** -- remote script execution is blocked on the servers
- After publishing, run `IIS-DeployApp.ps1 -SiteName GenericLogHandler` to copy from staging to IIS install path and recycle the app pool. Only use `IIS-RedeployAll.ps1` when `/deployAll` is requested.

## Server-Side IIS Deployment (IIS-DeployApp)

IIS deployment is handled by the **generic IIS-DeployApp system** in `C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\WebSites\IIS-DeployApp\`. This system manages **all** IIS virtual applications (DedgeAuth, GenericLogHandler, DocView, ServerMonitorDashboard, AutoDoc) using JSON deploy profiles.

| Script | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `IIS-DeployApp.ps1` | Deploy or update an IIS virtual app from a `.deploy.json` profile |
| `IIS-UninstallApp.ps1` | Remove an IIS virtual app and its app pool |
| `IIS-RedeployAll.ps1` | Full teardown + iisreset + rebuild all apps from templates |
| `Test-IISSite.ps1` | Run diagnostics and health checks on a deployed site |
| `_deploy.ps1` | Push scripts and templates to `*fkxtst-app` servers |

### Deploy Profile for DedgeAuth

DedgeAuth's deploy profile: `templates\DedgeAuth_WinApp.deploy.json`

```json
{
  "SiteName": "DedgeAuth",
  "PhysicalPath": "$env:OptPath\\DedgeWinApps\\DedgeAuth",
  "AppType": "AspNetCore",
  "DotNetDll": "DedgeAuth.Api.dll",
  "InstallSource": "WinApp",
  "VirtualPath": "/DedgeAuth",
  "ParentSite": "Default Web Site",
  "HealthEndpoint": "/health",
  "ApiPort": 8100
}
```

Deploy steps on the server: Teardown existing → Install files (WinApp) → Create app pool → Create virtual app → Generate web.config → Set permissions → Start → Health check

### Deploy Profiles for All Apps

| Profile | SiteName | AppType | InstallSource | ApiPort | HealthEndpoint |
|---------|----------|---------|---------------|---------|----------------|
| `DedgeAuth_WinApp.deploy.json` | DedgeAuth | AspNetCore | WinApp | 8100 | /health |
| `GenericLogHandler_WinApp.deploy.json` | GenericLogHandler | AspNetCore | WinApp | 8110 | /health |
| `DocView_WinApp.deploy.json` | DocView | AspNetCore | WinApp | 8282 | (none) |
| `ServerMonitorDashboard_WinApp.deploy.json` | ServerMonitorDashboard | AspNetCore | WinApp | 8998 | /api/IsAlive |
| `AutoDoc_None.deploy.json` | AutoDoc | Static | None | 0 | (none) |
| `DefaultWebSite_None.deploy.json` | DefaultWebSite | Static | None | 0 | (none) |

Profile naming convention: `<SiteName>_<InstallSource>.deploy.json`

## DedgeAuth-Specific Server Scripts (DedgePsh)

DedgeAuth-specific scripts live in `C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\WebSites\DedgeAuth\` -- there are NO local copies in this project.

| Script | Location | Deploy Target | Purpose |
|--------|----------|---------------|---------|
| Database setup | `DedgeAuth-DatabaseSetup\DedgeAuth-DatabaseSetup.ps1` | `*fkxtst-db` | PostgreSQL database + role setup |
| App registration | `DedgeAuth-AddAppSupport\DedgeAuth-AddAppSupport.ps1` | (all servers) | Register apps in DedgeAuth DB, create IIS deploy templates |

**Note:** The old `DedgeAuth-IISConfig` folder no longer exists. IIS configuration for all apps (including DedgeAuth) is now handled by the generic `IIS-DeployApp` system described above.

- **Always edit the files at the DedgePsh paths above** -- not in this project
- Distribution to servers is handled automatically by `Build-And-Publish.ps1` (runs each `_deploy.ps1` after every publish)

## Log Files

### Application Logs (Serilog)

Written to `%OptPath%\data\DedgeAuth\Logs\` using Serilog with daily rolling files.

| Method | Path |
|--------|------|
| **UNC path** | `C:\opt\src\DedgeSrc\DedgeSystemTools\Folders\Opt\data\DedgeAuth\Logs\DedgeAuth-YYYYMMDD.log` |
| **Local path on server** | `E:\opt\data\DedgeAuth\Logs\DedgeAuth-YYYYMMDD.log` |
| **API endpoint** | `GET /api/debug/logfile` (requires GlobalAdmin JWT) |

- The API endpoint returns today's log file path (local + UNC), existence, and size.
- Log files are retained for 31 days.
- If `%OptPath%` is not set, the application **will not start** and sends an SMS alert.

### IIS-DeployApp Logs

IIS deployment operations are logged separately:

| Method | Path |
|--------|------|
| **UNC path** | `C:\opt\src\DedgeSrc\DedgeSystemTools\Folders\Opt\data\IIS-DeployApp\FkLog_YYYYMMDD.log` |
| **Local path on server** | `$env:OptPath\data\IIS-DeployApp\FkLog_YYYYMMDD.log` |

- Written by `IIS-DeployApp.ps1`, `Test-IISSite.ps1`, `IIS-RedeployAll.ps1`, etc.
- Use these logs to diagnose IIS deployment failures, health check results, and app startup issues.

## 2. Git add, commit, and push

### /commit (default, this repo only)
- **git add** – Stage changes in this repo only.
- **git commit** – Commit with a message that describes what has changed.
- **git push** – Push to the remote.

### /commitAll (all affected repos)
- Stage, commit, and push changes across all affected repos (e.g. DedgeAuth, GenericLogHandler, DedgePsh).
- Only use when changes span multiple repositories.
